@opindex -h
@opindex -help
@opindex -v
The @samp{-h} and @samp{-help} options print brief usage information
on standard output and exit.  The @samp{-v} option prints the system
version string, system time stamp, operating system type, and
configure script options on standard output and exits.

@opindex -i
The @samp{-i} option can be used to force @code{gsc} to process the
command line like the interpreter.  The only difference with the
interpreter is that the compilation related procedures listed in this
chapter are also available (i.e. @code{compile-file},
@code{compile-file-to-target}, etc).

@node GSC interactive mode, GSC customization, GSC, GSC
@section Interactive mode

When no command line argument is present other than options @code{gsc}
behaves like @code{gsi} in interactive mode.

@node GSC customization, GSC batch mode, GSC interactive mode, GSC
@section Customization

@opindex -f
Like the interpreter, the compiler will examine the initialization
file unless the @samp{-f} option is specified.  Runtime options are
explained in @ref{Runtime options}.

@node GSC batch mode, Link files, GSC customization, GSC
@section Batch mode

@pindex gsc
@flindex .scm
@flindex .sld
@flindex .six
@flindex .c
@flindex .js
@flindex @var{file}.scm
@flindex @var{file}.sld
@flindex @var{file}.six
@flindex @var{file}.c
@flindex @var{file}.js
In batch mode @code{gsc} accepts on the command line 3 types of
non-options which are processed from left to right: @dfn{search
directories}, @dfn{modules}, and @dfn{files}.  Search directories are
added to the list of module search order directories.  Every command
line argument that is the name of a module that is found in the list
of module search order directories will cause that module to be
compiled.  Similarly, file names (with either no extension, or a C
file extension, or some other extension) on the command line will
cause that file to be compiled.  The compilation is done for the
target language specified with the @code{-target} @var{target} option.
@var{target} is either @code{js}, for JavaScript, or @code{C}, which
is the default if no target language is specified.

The recognized C file extensions are @samp{.c}, @samp{.C}, @samp{.cc},
@samp{.cp}, @samp{.cpp}, @samp{.CPP}, @samp{.cxx}, @samp{.c++},
@samp{.m}, @samp{.M}, and @samp{.mm}.

The extension can be omitted from a file name when the Scheme file has
a @samp{.scm}, @samp{.sld} or @samp{.six} extension.  When the
extension of the Scheme file is @samp{.six} the content of the file
will be parsed using the Scheme infix syntax extension (see
@ref{Scheme infix syntax extension}). Otherwise, @code{gsc} will parse
the Scheme file using the normal Scheme prefix syntax.  Files with a C
file extension must have been previously produced by @code{gsc} with
the @code{C} target and the @samp{-c} option, and are used by the
@code{C} target Gambit linker.

For each Scheme file the compiler creates a file of target code,
either @samp{@var{file}.c} or @samp{@var{file}.js} for the @code{C}
and @code{js} targets respectively.  The file's name is the same as
the Scheme file, but the extension is changed to @samp{.c} or
@samp{.js} as appropriate.  By default the file is created in the
same directory as the Scheme file.  This default can be overridden
with the compiler's @samp{-o} option.

The files of target code produced by the compiler serve two purposes.
They will be processed by a C compiler or JavaScript VM, and they also
contain information to be read by Gambit's linker to generate a
@dfn{link file}.  The link file is a file of target code that collects
various linking information for a group of modules, such as the set of
all symbols and global variables used by the modules.
@opindex -link
@opindex -exe
The linker is only invoked when the @samp{-link} or @samp{-exe}
options appear on the command line.

Compiler options must be specified before the first file name and
after the @samp{-:} runtime option (@pxref{Runtime options}).  If
present, the @samp{-i}, @samp{-f}, and @samp{-v} compiler options
must come first.  The available options are:

@cindex compiler options
@cindex options, compiler
