@node R7RS Compatible Modules, Installing Modules, Primitive Procedures, Modules
@section R7RS Compatible Modules

The R7RS Scheme standard specifies a modularization approach based on
the concept of library.  A library is defined using the
@code{define-library} form.  This form is implemented as a macro that
expands into the constructs used by primitive modules, in particular a
@code{##namespace} declaration with a namespace derived from the
library's name so that all variables defined by the library are in
that namespace.  With the @code{define-library} form the @code{angle3}
module example given previously can be written like this:

@smallexample
;;;---------------------------------------- file: @b{angle3.sld}
(define-library (angle3)

  (export deg->rad rad->deg)

  (import (scheme base)
          (scheme inexact))

  (begin
    (define factor (/ (atan 1) 45))
    (define (deg->rad x) (* x factor))
    (define (rad->deg x) (/ x factor))))
@end smallexample

For this library the expansion of the @code{define-library} form will
contain a @code{##namespace} declaration that causes the definition of
the global variables @code{angle3#factor}, @code{angle3#deg->rad}, and
@code{angle3#rad->deg}.  Meanwhile an @code{(import (angle3))} in
another library will generate a @code{##namespace} declaration that
maps uses of @code{deg->rad} and @code{rad->deg} to the global
variables @code{angle3#deg->rad} and @code{angle3#rad->deg}
respectively (note that the unexported global variable @code{factor}
is not included in the generated @code{##namespace} declaration).

For more complex libraries whose code is split into multiple files it
is convenient to put all the files in a dedicated subdirectory.  This
is the preferred filesystem structure for a library but the runtime
system supports both styles.  The previous module could be structured
like this instead:

@smallexample
;;;---------------------------------------- file: @b{angle3/angle3.sld}
(define-library (angle3)

  (export deg->rad rad->deg)

  (import (scheme base)
          (scheme inexact))

  (include "angle3.scm")) ;; path is relative to angle3.sld file

;;;---------------------------------------- file: @b{angle3/angle3.scm}
(define factor (/ (atan 1) 45))
(define (deg->rad x) (* x factor))
(define (rad->deg x) (/ x factor))
@end smallexample

@subsection Identifying libraries

Each library is given a name so that it can be referred to in various
contexts, most notably in @code{import} forms and the interpreter's
and compiler's command line.  The R7RS defines a library name
as a list whose members are identifiers and exact non-negative
integers, for example @code{(widget)}, @code{(_hamt)}, @code{(scheme
base)}, and @code{(srfi 64)}.

The system maps these R7RS library names to module identifiers that
are symbols formed by concatenating the parts of the library name
separated with @code{/}.  The library name and module name
are interchangeable.  Consequently, @code{(import srfi/64)} and
@code{(import _hamt)} are respectively equivalent to @code{(import
(srfi 64))} and @code{(import (_hamt))}.  Using the module name to
identify libraries on the command line is convenient as it avoids
having to escape parentheses and spaces.

@subsection The @code{define-library} form

@deffn {special form} define-library @var{name} @var{declaration} @dots{}
@end deffn

In a library definition @var{name} specifies the name of the library
and @var{declaration} is one of:

@example
(export @r{@var{<export spec>}} ...)
(import @r{@var{<import set>}} ...)
(begin @r{@var{<command or definition>}} ...)
(include @r{@var{<filename>}} ...)
(include-ci @r{@var{<filename>}} ...)
(include-library-declarations @r{@var{<filename>}} ...)
(cond-expand @r{@var{<cond expand features>}} ...)
(namespace @r{@var{<namespace>}})
(cc-options @r{@var{<options>}} ...)
(ld-options @r{@var{<options>}} ...)
(ld-options-prelude @r{@var{<options>}} ...)
(pkg-config @r{@var{<options>}} ...)
(pkg-config-path @r{@var{<path>}} ...)
@end example

@subsection @code{(export @r{@var{<export spec>}} ...)}

An @code{export} declaration specifies a list of identifiers which
can be made visible to other libraries or programs.
An @var{<export spec>} takes one of the following forms:

@example
@r{@var{<identifier>}}
(rename @r{@var{<identifier>1}} @r{@var{<identifier>2}})
@end example

In an @var{<export spec>}, an @var{<identifier>} names a single
binding (variable or macro) defined within or imported into the library, where the
external name for the export is the same as the name of the binding
within the library. A @code{rename} spec exports the binding
defined within or imported into the library and named by
@var{<identifier>1} in each
@code{(@r{@var{<identifier>1}} @r{@var{<identifier>2}})} pairing,
using @var{<identifier>2} as the external name.

@subsection @code{(import @r{@var{<import set>}} ...)}

A library declares a dependency to another library with the
@code{import} declaration.  The @code{(import @r{@var{<import set>}}
...)}  form identifies the imported library or libraries.

Each @var{<import set>} names a set of bindings
from a library and possibly specifies local names for the
imported bindings. An @var{<import set>} takes one of the following forms:

@example
@r{@var{<library name>}}
(only @r{@var{<import set>}} @r{@var{<identifier>}} ...)
(except @r{@var{<import set>}} @r{@var{<identifier>}} ...)
(prefix @r{@var{<import set>}} @r{@var{<identifier>}})
(rename @r{@var{<import set>}} (@r{@var{<identifier>1}} @r{@var{<identifier>2}}) ...)
@end example

In the first form, all of the identifiers in the named library's @code{export}
clauses are imported with the same names (or the exported names if
exported with @code{rename}).  The additional @var{<import set>}
forms modify this set as follows:

@itemize @bullet{}

@item
@code{only} produces a subset of the given
@var{<import set>} including only the listed identifiers (after any
renaming).  It is an error if any of the listed identifiers are
not found in the original set.

@item
@code{except} produces a subset of the given
@var{<import set>}, excluding the listed identifiers (after any
renaming). It is an error if any of the listed identifiers are not
found in the original set.

@item
@code{rename} modifies the given @var{<import set>},
replacing each instance of @var{<identifier>1} with
@var{<identifier>2}. It is an error if any of the listed
@var{<identifier>1}s are not found in the original set.

@item
@code{prefix} automatically renames all identifiers in
the given @var{<import set>}, prefixing each with the specified
@var{<identifier>}.

@end itemize

It is an error to import the same identifier more than once with
different bindings, or to redefine or mutate an imported binding with
a definition or with @code{set!}, or to refer to an identifier before
it is imported.

As an extension to the R7RS syntax it is allowed for a @var{<library
name>} to contain a trailing @code{@@@r{@var{version}}} when the
library is hosted in a @code{git} repository.  The @var{version} must
match a tag of that repository and it indicates the specific library
version required.  For example, @code{(import (github.com/gambit hello
@@1.0))} or equivalently @code{(import github.com/gambit/hello@@1.0)}.
Note that the version specifier is not separated with a @code{/} in
the module name.

Another extension to the R7RS syntax when the library is hosted in a
@code{git} repository is the use of dots before the name of the
library to indicate a relative reference within the repository.  The
number of dots indicates the number of parent hops.  For example, in
the library @code{(github.com/gambit hello demo)} an @code{(import
(.. hello))} will resolve to the @code{(github.com/gambit hello)}
library.  A relative library reference should not contain an explicit
@code{@@@r{@var{version}}} because the @var{version} is implicitly the
same as the referring module.

@subsection @code{(begin @r{@var{<command or definition>}} ...)}, @code{(include @r{@var{<filename>}} ...)}, and @code{(include-ci @r{@var{<filename>}} ...)}

The @code{begin}, @code{include}, and @code{include-ci} declarations are
used to specify the body of
the library.  They have the same syntax and semantics as the corresponding
expression types.
This form of @code{begin} is analogous to, but not the same as, the
two types of @code{begin} expressions.

@subsection @code{(include-library-declarations @r{@var{<filename>}} ...)}

The @code{include-library-declarations} declaration is similar to
@code{include} except that the contents of the file are spliced directly into the
current library definition.  This can be used, for example, to share the
same @code{export} declaration among multiple libraries as a simple
form of library interface.

@subsection @code{(cond-expand @r{@var{<cond expand features>}} ...)}

The @code{cond-expand} declaration has the same syntax and semantics as
the @code{cond-expand} expression type, except that it expands to
spliced-in library declarations rather than expressions enclosed in @code{begin}.

@subsection Extensions to the R7RS library declarations

The @code{(namespace @r{@var{<namespace>}})} declaration allows
overriding the namespace used for the library.  This is mainly useful
for system libraries to prevent namespace prefixing using a
@code{(namespace "")} declaration.

The remaining declarations are relevant to the @code{C} target and
ignored otherwise.  They provide information, in the form of strings,
to be passed to the compiler options of the same name when this library
is compiled:

@itemize @bullet{}

@item
@code{(cc-options @r{@var{<options>}} ...)}

@item
@code{(ld-options @r{@var{<options>}} ...)}

@item
@code{(ld-options-prelude @r{@var{<options>}} ...)}

@item
@code{(pkg-config @r{@var{<options>}} ...)}

@item
@code{(pkg-config-path @r{@var{<path>}} ...)}

@end itemize

For example, a library could force the C compiler to generate
machine code for i386 with:

@smallexample
(define-library (foo)
  (export bar)
  (import (scheme base))
  (cc-options "-march=i386") ;; request compilation for i386
  (begin (define (bar) 42)))
@end smallexample

@node Installing Modules, Compiling Modules, R7RS Compatible Modules, Modules
@section Installing Modules

When a module is imported, the processing of the @code{import} form
must locate and read the source code of the module at macro expansion
time to determine which names are exported and to what they are
mapped.  The list of module search directories (@code{~~lib} followed
by @code{~~userlib} by default) is searched to find the module's
source code.  At execution time the same search algorithm is used to
locate and load the module, either in source code form or compiled
form.  The @code{~~lib} directory is where the system's builtin
modules are put when Gambit is installed.  The @code{~~userlib}
directory is a convenient place where other modules can be installed
by the user because locating them does not require extending the list
of module search directories.

@deffn procedure module-search-order-reset!
@deffnx procedure module-search-order-add! @var{dir}

The list of module search directories can be modified using the
procedures @code{module-search-order-reset!} and
@code{module-search-order-add!} that respectively clear the list and
extend the list with the directory @var{dir} which must be a
string. The list can also be extended by using the
@code{-:search=}@var{DIR} runtime option or by a command line argument
to @code{gsi} and @code{gsc} that ends with a path separator or a
@samp{.} (@pxref{##demand-module and ##supply-module forms}).

For example:

@smallexample
$ @b{cat foobar.sld}
(define-library (foobar)
  (import (scheme write))
  (begin (display "foobar library has executed\n")))
$ @b{gsi}
Gambit @value{VERSION}

> @b{(import (foobar))}
*** ERROR IN (stdin)@@1.9 -- Cannot find library (foobar)
> @b{(module-search-order-add! ".")}
> @b{(import (foobar))}
foobar library has executed
> @b{,q}
$ @b{gsi -:search=. foobar}
foobar library has executed
$ @b{gsi . foobar}
foobar library has executed
@end smallexample

@end deffn

@deffn procedure module-whitelist-reset!
@deffnx procedure module-whitelist-add! @var{source}

When modules are installed it is done at the granularity of a
@dfn{package}, which is defined as a @code{git} repository possibly
containing more than one module.  For example, if the hosted module
@code{github.com/gambit/hello/demo} needs to be installed it is all of
the code at @code{github.com/gambit/hello} that is installed (this
includes the three modules @code{github.com/gambit/hello},
@code{github.com/gambit/hello/demo}, and
@code{github.com/gambit/hello/test}).

For convenience the runtime system will automatically install in the
@code{~~userlib} directory any hosted module that is from a trusted
source.  The whitelist of trusted sources, which initially contains
only @code{github.com/gambit}, can be modified using the procedures
@code{module-whitelist-reset!} and @code{module-whitelist-add!} that
respectively clear the list and extend the list with the source
@var{source} which must be a string, symbol or list specifying a hosted module reference. The list can also be extended
with the @code{-:whitelist=}@var{SOURCE} runtime option.

For example:

@smallexample
$ @b{gsi github.com/gambit/hello/demo  @r{@i{# auto-install of github.com/gambit/hello package}}}
People customarily greet each other when they meet.
In English you can say: hello Bob, nice to see you!
In French you can say: bonjour Bob, je suis enchant@'e!
Demo source code: /Users/feeley/.gambit_userlib/github.com/gambit/hello/@@/demo.scm
$ @b{gsi github.com/feeley/roman/demo  @r{@i{# no auto-install because not on whitelist}}}
*** ERROR IN ##main -- No such file or directory
(load "github.com/feeley/roman/demo")
$ @b{gsi -:whitelist=github.com/feeley github.com/feeley/roman/demo}
1 is I in roman numerals
2 is II in roman numerals
4 is IV in roman numerals
8 is VIII in roman numerals
16 is XVI in roman numerals
32 is XXXII in roman numerals
64 is LXIV in roman numerals
$ @b{gsi github.com/feeley/roman/demo   @r{@i{# OK because module is now installed}}}
1 is I in roman numerals
2 is II in roman numerals
4 is IV in roman numerals
8 is VIII in roman numerals
16 is XVI in roman numerals
32 is XXXII in roman numerals
64 is LXIV in roman numerals
$ @b{gsi github.com/feeley/roman/test   @r{@i{# the test module was also installed}}}
*** all tests passed out of a total of 19 tests
@end smallexample

The use of the runtime option @code{-:whitelist=} (with no @var{SOURCE})
will disable the automatic installation of modules, even from
@code{github.com/gambit}.  For example:

@smallexample
$ @b{gsi -:whitelist= github.com/gambit/hello/demo}
*** ERROR IN ##main -- No such file or directory
(load "github.com/gambit/hello/demo")
@end smallexample

@opindex -install
@opindex -uninstall
@opindex -upgrade
A manual management of packages is nevertheless possible with the
@code{gsi} package management operations.  These are invoked with the
command line options @samp{-install}, @samp{-uninstall}, and
@samp{-update} which respectively install, uninstall and update
packages.  The package management operations accept a list of
packages.  Packages are installed in @code{~~userlib} which is mapped
to @code{~/.gambit_userlib} by default.  An optional
@samp{-dir @var{dir}} option can be used to install the package in
some other directory.

For example:

@smallexample
$ @b{gsi -install github.com/feeley/roman}
installing github.com/feeley/roman to /Users/feeley/.gambit_userlib/
$ @b{gsi github.com/feeley/roman/demo}
1 is I in roman numerals
2 is II in roman numerals
4 is IV in roman numerals
8 is VIII in roman numerals
16 is XVI in roman numerals
32 is XXXII in roman numerals
64 is LXIV in roman numerals
$ @b{gsi -uninstall github.com/feeley/roman}
uninstalling github.com/feeley/roman from /Users/feeley/.gambit_userlib/
$ @b{gsi -install -dir ~/mylibs github.com/feeley/roman}
installing github.com/feeley/roman to /Users/feeley/mylibs
$ @b{gsi ~/mylibs/ github.com/feeley/roman/demo}
1 is I in roman numerals
2 is II in roman numerals
4 is IV in roman numerals
8 is VIII in roman numerals
16 is XVI in roman numerals
32 is XXXII in roman numerals
64 is LXIV in roman numerals
@end smallexample

Local @code{git} repositories can also be installed manually with the
package management operations using a path to the local repository.
This can be useful during the development phase before a library
becomes hosted.

For example:

@smallexample
$ @b{mkdir some}
$ @b{mkdir some/dir}
$ @b{mkdir some/dir/mylib}
$ @b{cd some/dir/mylib}
$ @b{cat > mylib.sld
(define-library (mylib)
  (import (scheme write))
  (begin (display "mylib library has executed\n")))}
$ @b{git init}
Initialized empty Git repository in /Users/feeley/doc/some/dir/mylib/.git/
$ @b{git add mylib.sld}
$ @b{git commit -m "first commit"}
[master (root-commit) c3f6aff] first commit
 1 file changed, 3 insertions(+)
 create mode 100644 mylib.sld
$ @b{cd ../../..}
$ @b{gsi some/dir/ mylib   @r{@i{# execution of mylib without installation}}}
mylib library has executed
$ @b{gsi -install some/dir/mylib}
installing some/dir/mylib to /Users/feeley/.gambit_userlib/
$ @b{gsi mylib   @r{@i{# execution of mylib after installation}}}
mylib library has executed
@end smallexample

@end deffn

@node Compiling Modules, , Installing Modules, Modules
@section Compiling Modules

When @code{gsc} finds a command line argument that is the name of a
module found on the list of module search order directories (after an
automatic installation if that is appropriate) that module's main
source code file will be compiled.

When a dynamic compilation is requested (which is the default
compilation mode and when the command line option @code{-dynamic} is
used) the compiler will compile for the selected target the main
source code file to a target file and a dynamically loadable object
file with a @samp{.o1} extension.  These files will be created in a
directory next to the module's main source code file, with the same
name stripped of it's extension and suffixed with the Gambit version
and the target name.  This naming strategy aims to avoid loading the
compiled file in an inappropriate context.  The module loading
algorithm knows it should check this directory to find a compiled
version of the module.

For example:

@smallexample
$ @b{mkdir lib1 lib2}
$ @b{cat > lib1/lib1.sld
(define-library (lib1)
  (export fact)
  (import (scheme base) (scheme write))
  (begin
    (define (fact n) (if (<= n 1) 1 (* n (fact (- n 1)))))
    (display "lib1 loaded\n")))}
$ @b{cat > lib2/lib2.sld
(define-library (lib2)
  (import (lib1) (scheme base) (scheme write))
  (begin
    (display
     (cond-expand
       ((compilation-target C)   "lib2 compiled to C\n")
       ((compilation-target (_)) "lib2 interpreted\n")
       (else                     "lib2 compiled to other\n")))
    (display (fact 10))
    (newline)))}
$ @b{gsi . lib2        @r{@i{# loads lib1.sld and lib2.sld}}}
lib1 loaded
lib2 interpreted
3628800
lib1
$ @b{tree --charset=ascii --noreport lib1 lib2}
`-- lib1.sld
lib2
`-- lib2.sld
$ @b{gsc . lib1 lib2   @r{@i{# compile lib1.sld and lib2.sld using C target}}}
$ @b{gsi . lib2        @r{@i{# loads generated lib1.o1 and lib2.o1}}}
lib1 loaded
lib2 compiled to C
3628800
$ @b{gsc -target js . lib1 lib2   @r{@i{# also compile them for js target}}}
$ @b{tree --charset=ascii --noreport lib1 lib2}
lib1
|-- lib1.sld
|-- lib1@@gambit409003@@C
|   |-- lib1.c
|   `-- lib1.o1
`-- lib1@@gambit409003@@js
    |-- lib1.js
    `-- lib1.o1
lib2
|-- lib2.sld
|-- lib2@@gambit409003@@C
|   |-- lib2.c
|   `-- lib2.o1
`-- lib2@@gambit409003@@js
    |-- lib2.js
    `-- lib2.o1
@end smallexample

To create an executable program from a set of non-legacy modules
it is important to use the @code{-nopreload} linking option when linking so
that the modules will be initialized in an order that is consistent
with the module dependencies.  If the default @code{-preload} linking option
is used some modules may be initialized out of order, leading to incorrect
execution.

Here is an example that extends the previous example:

@smallexample
$ @b{gsc -exe -nopreload . lib1/lib1.sld lib2/lib2.sld}
$ @b{lib2/lib2}
lib1 loaded
lib2 compiled to C
3628800
$ @b{gsc -target js -exe -nopreload . lib1/lib1.sld lib2/lib2.sld}
$ @b{lib2/lib2}
lib1 loaded
lib2 compiled to other
3628800
@end smallexample

