@subsection SIX semantics

The semantics of SIX depends on the definition of the
@code{six.@var{XXX}} identifiers (as procedures and macros).  Many of
these identifiers are predefined macros which give SIX a semantics
that is close to C's while also borrowing some semantics from
JavaScript and Python (such as @code{===} @code{in}, @code{**}, @code{//}).
The programmer may override these definitions to
change the semantics either globally or locally.  For example,
@code{six.x^y} is a predefined macro that expands @code{(six.x^y x y)}
into @code{(bitwise-xor x y)}.  If the programmer prefers the @code{^}
operator to express exponentiation in a specific procedure, then in
that procedure @code{six.x^y} can be redefined as a macro that expands
@code{(six.x^y x y)} into @code{(expt x y)}.  Note that the
associativity and precedence of operators cannot be changed as that is
a syntactic issue, so this will give a left associative exponentiation
operator with an unusual precedence.

Note that some identifiers do not have a predefined semantics and
are undefined identifiers, for example:
@code{six.label}, @code{six.goto}, @code{six.switch}, @code{six.case},
@code{six.break}, @code{six.continue}, @code{six.return},
@code{six.clause}, @code{six.x:-y}, @code{six.@@}, @code{six.@@=},
@code{six.import}, @code{six.from-import}, @code{six.from-import-*},
and @code{six.!}.

Here is an example showing some of the predefined syntax and
semantics of SIX:

@smallexample
> @b{(list (+ 1 2) \3+4 (+ 5 6))}
(3 7 11)
> @b{\[ 1+2, \(+ 3 4), 5+6 ]}
(3 7 11)
> @b{(map (lambda (x) \(x*x-1)/log(x+1)) '(1 2 3 4))}
(0 2.730717679880512 5.7707801635558535 9.320024018394177)
> @b{(map \function (x) @{ return (x*x-1)/log(x+1); @} '(1 2 3 4))}
(0. 2.730717679880512 5.7707801635558535 9.320024018394177)
> @b{\map(function (x) @{ return (x*x-1)/log(x+1); @}, [1, 2, 3, 4])}
(0. 2.730717679880512 5.7707801635558535 9.320024018394177)
